## Migration: `TimedExecutor` (.NET Framework ŌåÆ .NET 8)

**Pattern identified: Timeout enforcement** ŌĆö a thread runs work and is forcibly aborted if it exceeds a deadline.

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The entire preemptive-abort model is removed ŌĆö you must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable ŌĆö always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (automatic via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed ŌĆö not needed |

### ŌÜĀ’ĖÅ Critical pitfall: cooperative cancellation can't stop uncooperative code

The original `Thread.Abort()` forcibly killed the thread mid-execution. **Cooperative cancellation cannot do this.** If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking synchronous call that never checks a token, cancellation won't interrupt it ŌĆö the task keeps running in the background even after you've thrown `TimeoutException`.

**If your `work` delegates are long-running, you must make them cooperate:**

```csharp
// Change the signature to accept a CancellationToken
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Callers must check the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

1. **Don't forget `using` on `CancellationTokenSource`** ŌĆö leaking it causes timer leaks.
2. **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** ŌĆö it's the clean way to add cancellable waiting. Don't use `task.Wait(timeout)` which doesn't throw the right exception.
3. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party libs, native calls) can't be cancelled cooperatively. Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort.
4. **`catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)`** ŌĆö the `when` guard distinguishes your timeout from an external cancellation the caller might have triggered.
